"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452118","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-25","<p>The Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency does not record pass rates for each constituent part of the UK. Pass rates by test centre are published on GOV.UK.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-02-25T12:35:48.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452118/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452118/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452118/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-10","Driving Tests","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the pass rates in driving tests were in each region and constituent part of the UK in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","26789"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452119","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-23","<p>The A1079 between Barnby Moor and Wilberfoss is a local road and as such is the responsibility of the East Riding of Yorkshire Council. I understand that this scheme has been identified as a priority by the East Riding of Yorkshire Council, but it will be for the Council and the Local Enterprise Partnership to identify future funding opportunities.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-02-23T11:59:52.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452119/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452119/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452119/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-10","A1079","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he plans to take to ensure that dualling of the A1079 between Barnby Moor and Wilberfoss goes ahead; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","26748"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452120","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-23","<p>The European Commission published its proposal for a new framework on motor vehicle type approval on 27 January 2016 and formal discussions with European partners have not started yet. This new proposal sets out a number of changes to the type approval system to bolster oversight of those undertaking the testing and assessment of new vehicles. The Government will be pressing to ensure that any new measures are proportionate and cost effective. The Department for Transport will consult widely on the changes being proposed. I have no plans to amend UK law until changes to the EU Framework have been agreed.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-02-23T11:54:07.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452120/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452120/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452120/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-10","Motor Vehicle Type Approval","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what changes the UK is discussing with its European partners to the EU Framework Directive in respect of commercial vehicle body building and conversion; what plans he has to bring forward legislative proposals to amend UK law on this matter; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","26749"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452121","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-23","<p>Certain zero emission technologies for transport refrigeration systems are already in use on the road. The UK industry has recently announced plans for on-road trials in 2016 of a new technology using a ‘liquid-air’ engine.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-02-23T11:34:44.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452121/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452121/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452121/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-10","Transport: Refrigeration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he expects the first on-road UK trial of zero-emission transport refrigeration units to take place; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Greg Knight","East Yorkshire","Sir Greg Knight","26750"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452122","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-25","<p>Decisions about the provision of bus services requiring subsidy remain a matter for individual English local authorities, in the light of their other spending priorities.</p><p> </p><p>The majority of public funding for local bus services is from the block grant that local authorities in England receive from the Department for Communities and Local Government. However, my Department also provides around £40m of Bus Service Operators Grant (BSOG) funding directly to English local authorities to help deliver bus services.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-02-25T15:17:33.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452122/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452122/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452122/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-10","Bus Services: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of the effect of recent changes to funding of bus services on the provision of those services.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","26741"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452123","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-25","<p>On 15 February 2016, we announced that the new Access fund would be launched for 2017/18, and would be preceded by a £20m Sustainable Travel Transition Year for 2016/17. I am able to confirm that all bids will need to demonstrate links to cycling and walking to successfully secure funding.</p><p> </p><p>I am not yet able to confirm how much of the Access fund will go towards cycling and walking initiatives, as the formal Access fund has not yet been launched and funding has not yet been allocated.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-02-25T15:45:37.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452123/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452123/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452123/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-10","Cycling: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much of the Access Fund he expects to be spent on cycling in each year to 2020-21.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","26736"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452124","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-25","<p>Due to the inclusion of devolved funding when reporting on overall cycling expenditure, spend is usually reported in terms of regions.</p><p> </p><p>Currently, spend on cycling is £6 per head across England compared to £2 per head in 2010, with spend of £10 in London and the eight Cycle Ambition Cities. Further details of funding programmes will be set out in the Cycling and Walking Investment Strategy to be published in summer 2016.</p><p>In the meantime, where funding is already allocated then the geographic distribution is known.</p><p> </p><p>Where funding has been subject to formula then the geographic distribution will be known at the point the formula weightings are determined.</p><p> </p><p>Where funding is allocated by competition, then the geographic distribution will be known at the point the results of the competition are announced.</p><p> </p><p>Where funding is devolved, then its geographic distribution is a matter for the relevant local body.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-02-25T15:32:58.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452124/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452124/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452124/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-10","Cycling: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 8 December 2015 to Question 18101, at what stage he plans to be able to predict the geographical distribution of funding for cycling outside of London and the eight cycling ambition cities; and what steps he is taking to identify that geographical distribution.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","26733"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452125","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-25","<p>On 15 February 2016, we announced that the new Access fund would be launched later in 2016 for delivery in 2017/18, and would be preceded by a £20m Sustainable Travel Transition Year for 2016/17.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-02-25T15:37:32.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452125/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452125/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452125/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-10","Transport: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans to announce details of the new Access Fund.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","26734"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452126","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-25","<p>On 15 February 2016, we announced that there will be a transition year between the Local Sustainable Transport Fund and the Access fund. The Sustainable Travel Transition Year will take place in 2016/17, with the Access fund being formally launched later in 2016 for delivery in 2017/18.</p><p> </p><p>This transition year will enable the Department time to publish the Cycling and Walking Investment Strategy (CWIS); to work with the Department of Communities and Local Government (CLG) to understand the future approach for the Local Growth Fund; and to identify the highest value for money approach to supporting investment in sustainable travel.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-02-25T15:41:29.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452126/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452126/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452126/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-10","Transport: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he plans for there to be a period between the Local Sustainable Transport Fund ending in March 2016 and the commencement of the new Access Fund.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","26735"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452127","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-22","<p>I am unable to provide this information as it is held by Network Rail and is commercially sensitive.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-02-22T15:55:15.1Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452127/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452127/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452127/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-10","Network Rail: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, by what proportion the rent for premises leased by Network Rail has increased for businesses based in (a) Bethnal Green and Bow constituency, (b) London and (c) England in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Rushanara Ali","Bethnal Green and Bow","Rushanara Ali","26725"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452128","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-25","<p>The M60 Smart Motorway project near Denton is currently in its early design stage and the scope and boundaries of the project are still being defined. By the nature, of this type of project, Highways England expect that the scheme will mostly be within the existing motorway footprint. This could include a quiet road surfacing or sound barriers.</p><p> </p><p>However, any compensation arrangements will be the same as for all such improvement schemes. If properties in the nearby area of the scheme qualify for noise insulation under the Noise Insulation Regulations, then appropriate offers will be made.</p><p> </p><p>The environmental impact will be assessed as part of the design and any necessary actions will be considered during the detailed design. One year after the completion of the scheme, local property owners may apply for compensation under Part I of the Land Compensation Act 1973 and such claims will be assessed under the terms of that Act.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-02-25T14:33:11.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452128/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452128/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452128/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-10","M60: Denton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he plans to include additional road surface noise reduction measures, a sound barrier and home noise insulation measures in the contract specifications for the M60 smart motorway extension through Denton.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","26868"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452129","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-25","<p>The M60 Smart Motorway Project near Denton is currently in its early design stage and the scope and boundaries of the project are still being defined. By its nature of this type of project, Highways England expect that the scheme will mostly be within the existing footprint.</p><p> </p><p>Any compensation arrangements will be the same as for all such improvement schemes. If there is a requirement to purchase land then the owners of that land can expect to be appropriately compensated. Similarly if properties in the area of the scheme qualify for noise insulation under the Noise Insulation Regulations, then appropriate offers will be made.</p><p> </p><p>The environmental impact will be assessed as part of the design and any necessary actions will be considered during the detailed design. One year after the completion of the scheme local property owners may apply for compensation under Part I of the Land Compensation Act 1973 and such claims will be assessed under the terms of that Act.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-02-25T14:37:04.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452129/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452129/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452129/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-10","M60: Denton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether he expects residents adjoining the M60 in Denton to qualify for monetary compensation for the extension of the smart motorway scheme.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","26869"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452130","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-22","<p>The Government sets noise abatement procedures at Heathrow, Gatwick and Stansted. These are set out in Noise Abatement Requirements Notice(s) made under section 78 of the Civil Aviation Act 1982.</p><p> </p><p>At other airports these are agreed locally often through local planning agreements. Where the Government sets the procedures these are monitored by the airports’ noise and track keeping systems which receives data from National Air Traffic Services (NATS) radars and permanent noise monitors located around the airport.</p><p> </p><p>Adherence to the noise abatement procedures are reported via the airports flight performance report which will be available on the airports website. Fines are imposed at Heathrow, Gatwick and Stansted airport for breaching noise departure limits.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-02-22T13:48:36.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452130/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452130/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452130/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-10","Aviation: Noise","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which body is responsible for enforcement of aircraft noise abatement requirements.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","26895"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452131","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-22","<p>The requirements are kept under review to take account of any relevant new evidence. However, I have no plans at present to update the Heathrow Airport London (Noise Abatement Requirements) Notice 2010.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-02-22T13:54:16.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452131/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452131/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452131/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-10","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will bring forward legislative proposals to update the Heathrow Airport London (Noise Abatement Requirements) Notice 2010 to require higher minimum rates of climb for aircraft taking off from Heathrow Airport.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","26896"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452132","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-22","<p>The Department for Transport (DfT) has not made any assessment of rates of climb from Heathrow airport compared to any other airports. The Government is aware of an independent report published last year on climb rates at Heathrow airport.</p><p> </p><p>The airport is working with the industry and the CAA to understand the issues and what this means from a noise perspective. DfT sits on the Heathrow Noise Community Forum where this work programme is being taken forward.</p><p> </p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-02-22T13:43:48.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452132/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452132/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452132/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-10","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of the rates of climb of aircraft taking off from Heathrow Airport compared to other (a) UK and (b) European airports.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","26882"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452133","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-25","<p>I refer the Hon Member to my previous answers to Questions 16782, 19723 and 19724.</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=16782" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=16782</a></p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=19723" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=19723</a></p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-12-11/19724/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-12-11/19724/</a></p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-02-25T15:57:48.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452133/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452133/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452133/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-10","Roads: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answers of 18 November 2015 to Question 16782 and of 11 December 2015 to Questions 19723 and 19724, if he will estimate how many miles of local authority road are in poor structural condition in England.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","26880"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452134","Wales Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>No staff in the Wales Office receive these allowances.</p>","Vale of Glamorgan","Alun Cairns",,"2016-02-25T12:52:08.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452134/answer","Biography information for Alun Cairns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452134/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452134/answer",,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-02-10","Wales Office: Fringe Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many staff in his Department receive (a) home to work travel allowance, (b) a car allowance and (c) subsidised health insurance.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","26828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452135","Women and Equalities","false","2016-02-25","<p>No staff receive the above allowances in the Government Equalities Office.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2016-02-25T16:57:01.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452135/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452135/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452135/answer",,,,,"31","Women and Equalities","Women and Equalities","2016-02-10","Government Equalities Office: Fringe Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for Women and Equalities, how many staff in the Government Equalities Office receive (a) home to work travel allowance, (b) a car allowance and (c) subsidised health insurance.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","26818"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452136","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-24","<p>The information below is as at 31 January 2016.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><ul><li>Home to work travel allowance - DWP and the Health and Safety Executive (HSE) pay excess fares only when an employee is</li></ul><p> </p><ol type="a"><ol type="a"><li>compulsorily transferred to another office at the department’s instigation and the cost of travelling to the new workplace is greater than the cost met by the employee in travelling to the previous workplace. Currently, there are 2,144 DWP employees (2.5% of workforce) and 44 HSE employees (1.59% of workforce) receiving excess fares. These payments are normally time-limited to 3 years, although can be for 5 years in exceptional circumstances. No other DWP non-departmental public bodies are making such payments.</li></ol></ol><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><ul><li>Car allowance – DWP currently pays a car allowance to 117 (0.14%) employees, who transferred into DWP from another employer. This is not an allowance that is available to other DWP employees, but DWP is legally obliged to honour the previous contractual agreement following the transfer. No other DWP non-departmental public bodies are making such payments.</li></ul><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><ul><li>Subsidised health insurance – From 31/03/16 no DWP employees will receive subsidised health insurance. The Pensions Advisory Service currently pays Benenden for healthcare cover on behalf of its 44 employees which was originally paid as a recruitment and retention benefit. This attracts a tax liability which is paid by TPAS as an organisation.</li></ul><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-02-24T14:22:33.633Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452136/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452136/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452136/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-10","Department for Work and Pensions: Fringe Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many staff in his Department and non-departmental public bodies receive (a) home to work travel allowance, (b) a car allowance and (c) subsidised health insurance.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","26829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452137","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-22","<p>DWP have published an estimate of the number of people who will reach State Pension age in 2016/17 in figure 24 of ‘Impact of New State Pension (nSP) on an Individual’s Pension Entitlement – Longer Term Effects of nSP’ which can be found at:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/491845/impact-of-new-state-pension-longer-term-reserach.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/491845/impact-of-new-state-pension-longer-term-reserach.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Information on the average new State Pension caseload in 2016/17 are published in table 2c of the ‘Autumn Statement 2015 Expenditure and caseloads’ publication, which is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/490307/outturn-and-forecast-autumn-statement-2015.xlsx" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/490307/outturn-and-forecast-autumn-statement-2015.xlsx</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Breakdowns by month are not available.</p><p> </p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-02-22T14:20:11.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452137/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452137/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452137/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-10","State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the number of people who will begin receiving the new state pension in April 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","26967"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452138","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-22","<p>The contract with Monster Worldwide Ltd was signed on 25 January 2012 and will end on 18 March 2017. The total contract value is £20,026,152. Payment is made monthly in arrears.</p><p> </p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-02-22T11:46:06.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452138/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452138/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452138/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-10","Department for Work and Pensions: Monster Worldwide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the duration and value is of his Department's contract with Monster Worldwide Ltd for the management of Universal Jobmatch; and on what basis payments to Monster Worldwide Ltd are made under that contract.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","26960"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452139","Department of Health","false","2016-02-24","<p>The Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority (HFEA) has advised that it has licensed one human embryo research project involving the use of genome editing CRISPR-Cas9. One objective of this project is to derive human embryonic stem cells. As outlined in the HFEA Inspection Report, there is no intention for these stem cells to be used in human application. In these circumstances, there is no need to assess whether they conform to good manufacturing practice and are classed as clinical grade.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-02-24T13:09:04.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452139/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452139/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452139/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-10","Stem Cells","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government under what circumstances embryonic stem cell lines that have been derived from human embryos subjected to genome editing by means of CRISPR-Cas9 would be considered to conform to good manufacturing practice and classed as clinical grade by either the Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority or the UK Stem Cell Bank.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL6086"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452140","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-24","<p>As stated in the previous responses, we remain deeply concerned about the human rights situation in the Democratic People’s Republic of Korea. The UN Commission of Inquiry report highlighted the horrific human rights violations perpetrated by the regime, including details of officials from state institutions and ministries.</p><p>The Government supports the principle that there must be no impunity for those accused of human rights violations and that crimes against humanity are appropriately investigated.</p><p>We will continue to work with members of the international community through multilateral fora, including the UN Security Council and the UN Human Rights Council, to ensure the regime is held to account for its appalling human rights record.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-02-24T17:35:01.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452140/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452140/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452140/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-10","North Korea: Crimes against Humanity","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Anelay of St Johns on 8 February (HL5360) and the Written Answer by the Minister of State for the Foreign and Commonwealth Office, Hugo Swire, on 29 January (HC23512), whether the UK will act on the information that officials from a number of state institutions and ministries of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea are responsible for possible crimes against humanity in North Korea, and ensure that there is no impunity for those accused of serious human rights violations.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL6087"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452141","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-24","<p>Our Ambassador to the Democratic People’s Republic of Korea (DPRK) and senior officials from the Foreign and Commonwealth Office (FCO) have met representatives of the DPRK on a number of occasions since 7 February 2014. These meetings are part of normal diplomatic business and play a crucial role in our policy of critical engagement with the DPRK. The FCO does not keep a record of the number of individual meetings.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-02-24T17:35:38.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452141/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452141/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452141/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-10","North Korea: Human Rights","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many meetings have been held between senior officials of the UK and representatives of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea since the release of the report of the UN Commission of Inquiry on 7 February 2014.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL6088"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452142","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-24","<p>Our Embassy in Pyongyang has met with a number of officials from various Democratic People’s Republic of Korea (DPRK) ministries since 7 February 2014. These meetings are part of normal diplomatic business and play a crucial role in our policy of critical engagement with the DPRK.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-02-24T17:37:28.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452142/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452142/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452142/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-10","North Korea: Human Rights","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government which Democratic People's Republic of Korea ministries' representatives the British Embassy in Pyongyang has met since the release of the report of the UN Commission of Inquiry on 7 February 2014.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL6089"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452143","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-24","<p>The Government fully cooperated with the Panel of Experts on this matter. Following a request to the Government for assistance, the Panel were put in direct contact with Princess Yachts International to follow up on their investigations.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-02-24T17:36:06.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452143/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452143/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452143/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-10","North Korea: Princess Yachts International","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why they did not respond to correspondence sent by the UN Panel of Experts, as listed in UN Security Council Report S/2015/131; and whether they have investigated the actions of Princess Yachts International in the light of the sighting of the Princess 95MY yacht in North Korea in 2013.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL6090"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452144","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-24","<p>Vessel registration is a matter for Flag state action. The UK is not a Flag state for any Democratic People’s Republic of Korea (DPRK) vessels, so has not been involved in investigating this issue. We have processes in place to verify the provenance of any vessel registered under the British flag.</p><p>There are documented links between the DPRK’s diplomatic missions and its proliferation activity which are in breach of sanctions. For example, the UN DPRK Panel of Experts reported that DPRK Embassy officials in Cuba were engaged in making arrangements for the 2013 Chong Chon Gang shipment of conventional arms and related materials in violation of UN Security Council Resolutions. We have since worked with partners to encourage the need for vigilance over possible illicit activity taking place by DPRK diplomatic missions.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-02-24T17:38:08.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452144/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452144/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452144/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-10","North Korea: Sanctions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they have taken to investigate and address the role of the Embassy of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea in London in evading UN Security Council sanctions in respect of their submission of vessel registration changes to the International Maritime Organisation in 2014; and what assessment they have made of the involvement of embassies of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea worldwide in sanctions evasion.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL6091"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452145","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-24","<p>Government has asked Nicola Shaw to undertake an independent report on the future shape and financing of Network Rail and it is up to her whether she chooses to publish the responses to her consultation.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-02-24T12:26:27.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452145/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452145/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452145/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-10","Network Rail","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they intend to publish responses to the consultation on the draft Shaw Report on the future structure of Network Rail.","false","Biography information for Lord Berkeley",,"Lord Berkeley","HL6092"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452146","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-24","<p>Nicola Shaw has been asked to produce an independent report into the future shape and financing of Network Rail and her work will look at all the options. Government has no pre-determined view of the right outcome and will not be dogmatic about the future shape of Network Rail as we want the right outcome for passengers and taxpayers. Government looks forward to receiving the final report and will respond in due course.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-02-24T12:25:32.94Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452146/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452146/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452146/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-10","Network Rail","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to consult on any recommendations contained in the Shaw Report on the future of Network Rail due to be published in March.","false","Biography information for Lord Berkeley",,"Lord Berkeley","HL6093"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452147","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-22","<p>Ministers have acknowledged that the £1 trillion target is a stretch; however, the Government has a clear strategy for increasing both the value of UK exports and the number of British exporters.</p><p> </p><p>Progress in delivering against the target will be reported through the ONS.</p>",,"Lord Maude of Horsham",,"2016-02-22T12:26:56.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452147/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452147/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452147/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Exports","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of whether they will meet their target of doubling exports by 2020.","false","Biography information for Baroness Burt of Solihull",,"Baroness Burt of Solihull","HL6094"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452148","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-22","<p>The government does not breakdown 2020 export forecasts geographically.</p><p>However, the independent Office for Budget Responsibility does publish UK total export forecasts up to 2020, with the most recent publication being in the November 2015 Economic and Fiscal Outlook:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Exports</p></td><td><p>Imports</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>533.6</p></td><td><p>556.8</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>557.4</p></td><td><p>581.4</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2018</p></td><td><p>585.4</p></td><td><p>609.5</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2019</p></td><td><p>616.3</p></td><td><p>639.0</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2020</p></td><td><p>648.0</p></td><td><p>669.7</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td colspan="4"><p>Source: November 2015 Economic and fiscal outlook</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>",,"Lord Maude of Horsham",,"2016-02-22T12:28:36.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452148/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452148/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452148/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Exports","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the proportion of exports that will be sold to other EU member states by 2020.","false","Biography information for Baroness Burt of Solihull",,"Baroness Burt of Solihull","HL6095"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452149","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-29","<p>At the February European Council meeting the Government negotiated a new settlement, giving the United Kingdom a special status in a reformed European Union (EU). The Government's view is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU.</p><p> </p><p>As part of the new settlement it was confirmed that the EU will pursue, with renewed commitment, free trade agreements with the world’s most dynamic economies, so that the tariff and regulatory barriers faced by UK companies in large and growing non-EU markets are reduced or eliminated. As an example, after the EU-South Korea deal came into force in 2011, UK exports to South Korea doubled in three years.</p><p> </p><p>These deals have the potential to boost UK exports significantly and can contribute to the Government’s 2020 target.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-02-29T12:15:14.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452149/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452149/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452149/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Exports","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the effect that the EU referendum will have on their target of doubling exports by 2020.","false","Biography information for Baroness Burt of Solihull",,"Baroness Burt of Solihull","HL6096"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452150","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-17","<p>Savings will be broadly delivered through implementing a new digital infrastructure to provide cost-effective access to export services; contractual efficiencies; and prioritising market and sector opportunities that will add most value to UK exports. This is about being more efficient and delivering for UK businesses, including through enhancing direct support and developing the private sector market.</p><p>HM Treasury has recognised the importance of the exports agenda by agreeing that £175m of further proposed savings between 2016-17 and 2019-20 should be reinvested in priority areas. The Government is committed to driving a step-change in UK exports and the reinvestment secured to refocus UK Trade &amp; Investment will help us deliver this.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Maude of Horsham",,"2016-02-17T14:05:33.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452150/answer","Biography information for Lord Maude of Horsham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452150/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452150/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Exports","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the impact on exports of the decision to reduce the budget of UK Trade and Investment.","false","Biography information for Baroness Burt of Solihull",,"Baroness Burt of Solihull","HL6097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452151","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-22","<p>Women are currently excluded from serving in ground close combat roles in the Infantry and Royal Armoured Corps, the Royal Marines and the Royal Air Force Regiment. The Prime Minister stated on 20 December 2015 that he would like to see all roles in the Armed Forces opened up to women in 2016. Further physiological research currently under way will inform a final decision in mid-2016.</p><p> </p><p>The review &quot;Women in Ground Close Combat&quot; has identified the principle of full integration as a vital element in generating cohesion in combat troops. The subsequent infrastructure work required is being considered as part of ongoing implementation planning, in the event that the exclusion is lifted. Early estimates from the 2014 research paper suggest that a fully integrated solution at the Army's Infantry Training Centre at Catterick could cost up to £1.6 million. Once a final decision is taken, the Department will be able to identify and cost a fully integrated long-term solution as required.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe","HL6099","2016-02-22T17:27:08.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452151/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452151/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452151/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-10","Army: Females","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what progress has been made in the integration of female soldiers into close combat units in the Army.","false","Biography information for Lord Campbell of Pittenweem",,"Lord Campbell of Pittenweem","HL6098"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452152","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-22","<p>Women are currently excluded from serving in ground close combat roles in the Infantry and Royal Armoured Corps, the Royal Marines and the Royal Air Force Regiment. The Prime Minister stated on 20 December 2015 that he would like to see all roles in the Armed Forces opened up to women in 2016. Further physiological research currently under way will inform a final decision in mid-2016.</p><p> </p><p>The review &quot;Women in Ground Close Combat&quot; has identified the principle of full integration as a vital element in generating cohesion in combat troops. The subsequent infrastructure work required is being considered as part of ongoing implementation planning, in the event that the exclusion is lifted. Early estimates from the 2014 research paper suggest that a fully integrated solution at the Army's Infantry Training Centre at Catterick could cost up to £1.6 million. Once a final decision is taken, the Department will be able to identify and cost a fully integrated long-term solution as required.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe","HL6098","2016-02-22T17:27:08.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452152/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452152/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452152/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-10","Army: Females","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what infrastructure preparations have been made for the integration of female soldiers into close combat units in the Army; and what is their estimate of the cost of any such preparations to date.","false","Biography information for Lord Campbell of Pittenweem",,"Lord Campbell of Pittenweem","HL6099"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452153","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-24","<p>This Government has always been clear that we are committed to supporting the most vulnerable people in our society. One person without a home is one too many. That is why we have protected the homelessness prevention funding local authorities receive, totalling £315 million by 2019-20. This builds on our commitment to increase central government funding for homelessness programmes to £139 million over the next four years.</p><p>We are working with homelessness organisations to consider other options, including legislation, to ensure those at risk of homelessness get earlier and more effective support. Through a series of roundtables we have already started conversations to help shape and inform our future approach to tackling homelessness and deciding our investment priorities.</p><p>During the last Parliament the Homelessness Prevention Grant and our investment in homelessness programmes helped prevent 935,800 households from becoming homeless.</p><p>We will continue to use the information provided to us by local authorities to assess the causes of homelessness and the extent of homelessness prevention and relief activity, in order to help shape future policy and investment.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-02-24T12:40:16.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452153/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452153/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452153/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-10","Homelessness","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have undertaken any analysis to determine why there has been an increase in the number of homeless people; and, if so, what assessment they have made of the impact of the Homeless Prevention Fund provided to local authorities and increased funding of programmes for the homeless.","false","Biography information for Baroness Gould of Potternewton",,"Baroness Gould of Potternewton","HL6100"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452154","Home Office","false","2016-02-22","<p>We have no plans to repeal the Vagrancy Act 1824.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2016-02-22T15:42:47.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452154/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452154/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452154/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-10","Begging and Vagrancy","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have any plans to repeal the provisions contained within the Vagrancy Act 1824, which allow for homeless people to be arrested for begging.","false","Biography information for Baroness Gould of Potternewton",,"Baroness Gould of Potternewton","HL6101"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452155","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>The announcement on 6 February was on a new clause for all government grant agreements. It is not specific to Charities.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley","HL6103","2016-02-25T17:48:48.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452155/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452155/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452155/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-10","Charities: Lobbying","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they consulted the Charity Commission prior to their announcement on 6 February that charities would no longer be able to use any government grant to influence policy, and if so, what advice the Charity Commission gave.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL6102"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452156","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>The announcement on 6 February was on a new clause for all government grant agreements. It is not specific to Charities.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley","HL6102","2016-02-25T17:48:48.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452156/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452156/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452156/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-10","Charities: Lobbying","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will suspend their new policy, announced on 6 February, on charitable sector campaigning, in the light of the announcement by the Cabinet Office minister Matthew Hancock MP that the sector would face additional restrictions on such activity, so as to allow time for parliamentary debate on this issue.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL6103"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452157","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-24","<p>The Government has not yet approved any country allocations from the Prosperity Fund.</p>",,"Baroness Verma",,"2016-02-24T12:25:05.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452157/answer","Biography information for Baroness Verma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452157/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452157/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-10","Prosperity Fund","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether their new prosperity fund will give priority to countries with large refugee and migrant populations, lack of own resources, or tourism reduced by wars, such as Lebanon, Jordan and Tunisia.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL6104"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452158","Home Office","false","2016-02-23","<p>In line with the UK-France Joint Declaration of 20 August 2015, the UK and France have increased the frequency of joint communications campaigns which involve speaking to migrants in Calais and Dunkirk to inform them of their options and providing advice on their rights to claim asylum in France. This includes speaking to vulnerable people and those who claim a link to family members in the UK. But we are very clear that the primary responsibility for the welfare and treatment of migrants in Calais lies with the French authorities.</p><p>A leaflet detailing the Dublin III Regulations is provided to applicants who have claimed asylum in France and indicate that they have family members in the UK.</p><p>The UK is also funding a project to identify those in the camps who are especially vulnerable and at risk of trafficking and exploitation, and to provide them with appropriate support within the French system.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL6106","2016-02-23T17:27:27.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452158/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452158/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452158/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-10","Refugees: France","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the remarks by Lord Bates on 9 February (HL Deb, col GC142), which British personnel or organisations are now "search[ing] out the most vulnerable in the camps at Calais and Dunkirk".","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL6105"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452159","Home Office","false","2016-02-23","<p>In line with the UK-France Joint Declaration of 20 August 2015, the UK and France have increased the frequency of joint communications campaigns which involve speaking to migrants in Calais and Dunkirk to inform them of their options and providing advice on their rights to claim asylum in France. This includes speaking to vulnerable people and those who claim a link to family members in the UK. But we are very clear that the primary responsibility for the welfare and treatment of migrants in Calais lies with the French authorities.</p><p>A leaflet detailing the Dublin III Regulations is provided to applicants who have claimed asylum in France and indicate that they have family members in the UK.</p><p>The UK is also funding a project to identify those in the camps who are especially vulnerable and at risk of trafficking and exploitation, and to provide them with appropriate support within the French system.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL6105","2016-02-23T17:27:27.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452159/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452159/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452159/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-10","Asylum: EU Law","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they or the EU plan to produce a simple guide to the Dublin III Regulations for potential applicants for asylum and their advisers; and if so, whether that guide will be made available, at least in English and French, at refugee camps in Calais and Dunkirk, and at other points of entry into the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL6106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452160","Home Office","false","2016-02-23","<p>The UK is in regular contact with France on all matters related to Calais and the migration situation, and engages with EU and multilateral partners, including the UN on a wide range of migration issues in order to find an effective and sustainable solution.</p><p>The management of the migrant camps in Calais is the responsibility of the French Government. However, we understand that the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) has made visits to the camps in Calais and Dunkirk, and we note the welcome given by the UNHCR to the joint declaration to address the issues in Calais signed by the UK and France on 20 August 2015.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2016-02-23T16:56:14.547Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452160/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452160/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452160/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-10","Refugees: France","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of whether the UN High Commissioner for Refugees has access to the refugees in camps at Calais and Dunkirk; and if not, whether they will discuss the matter with the government of France.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL6107"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452161","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-23","<p>I can sympathise with the anguish caused to the families of victims where the whereabouts of their loved one is unknown and the offender wilfully fails to co-operate. Such behaviour is already taken into account by the court when sentencing the offender, and by the independent Parole Board when assessing an offender’s eligibility for possible release. The Prisons Minister has written to the Parole Board asking it to consider reviewing its guidelines on this issue.</p>",,"Lord Faulks",,"2016-02-23T16:50:26.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452161/answer","Biography information for Lord Faulks","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452161/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452161/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-10","Homicide: Parole","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what stage they have reached in their consideration of amending legislation in order to ensure that convicted murderers who persist in refusing to reveal the location of bodies of victims are prevented from being released on parole; and when they expect to introduce legislation to that effect.","false","Biography information for Lord Maginnis of Drumglass",,"Lord Maginnis of Drumglass","HL6108"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452162","Department of Health","false","2016-02-24","<p>The Department of Health, Public Health England (PHE) or NHS England do not hold information about which laboratories are and are not International Organization for Standardization (ISO) 15189 accredited. A list of accredited laboratories is held on the United Kingdom Accreditation Service (UKAS) website and is the definitive list of accredited laboratories to which the Department, PHE and the NHS refer. Accreditation is covered by the Clinical Pathology Accreditation (CPA) company until recently, and is now part of the UKAS scheme.</p><p> </p><p>There is no intention to transfer the Lyme disease testing service from the Rare &amp; Imported Pathogens Laboratory (RIPL) to another laboratory. RIPL as a department will move from the Porton site as part of the PHE relocation scheduled to commence in 2018 but no decision on the exact date has been made. RIPL is scheduled to transfer to ISO 15189 in late summer 2016, when the ISO inspection team review the tests offered by the laboratory under ISO 15189. Until that time, the laboratory is operating under CPA in accordance with the transition process laid down by ISO.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL6110 ; HL6111","2016-02-24T13:10:52.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452162/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452162/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452162/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-10","Laboratories","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many NHS and Public Health England (PHE) medical or microbiology laboratories (1) are, and (2) are not, currently ISO 15189 accredited; and what is the schedule for such accreditation of NHS and PHE laboratories.","false","Biography information for The Countess of Mar",,"The Countess of Mar","HL6109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452163","Department of Health","false","2016-02-24","<p>The Department of Health, Public Health England (PHE) or NHS England do not hold information about which laboratories are and are not International Organization for Standardization (ISO) 15189 accredited. A list of accredited laboratories is held on the United Kingdom Accreditation Service (UKAS) website and is the definitive list of accredited laboratories to which the Department, PHE and the NHS refer. Accreditation is covered by the Clinical Pathology Accreditation (CPA) company until recently, and is now part of the UKAS scheme.</p><p> </p><p>There is no intention to transfer the Lyme disease testing service from the Rare &amp; Imported Pathogens Laboratory (RIPL) to another laboratory. RIPL as a department will move from the Porton site as part of the PHE relocation scheduled to commence in 2018 but no decision on the exact date has been made. RIPL is scheduled to transfer to ISO 15189 in late summer 2016, when the ISO inspection team review the tests offered by the laboratory under ISO 15189. Until that time, the laboratory is operating under CPA in accordance with the transition process laid down by ISO.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL6109 ; HL6111","2016-02-24T13:10:52.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452163/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452163/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452163/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-10","Lyme Disease","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many NHS and Public Health England laboratories that carry out Lyme borreliosis testing (1) are, and (2) are not, ISO 15189 accredited; and when they expect the Rare and Imported Pathogens Laboratory to be so accredited.","false","Biography information for The Countess of Mar",,"The Countess of Mar","HL6110"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452164","Department of Health","false","2016-02-24","<p>The Department of Health, Public Health England (PHE) or NHS England do not hold information about which laboratories are and are not International Organization for Standardization (ISO) 15189 accredited. A list of accredited laboratories is held on the United Kingdom Accreditation Service (UKAS) website and is the definitive list of accredited laboratories to which the Department, PHE and the NHS refer. Accreditation is covered by the Clinical Pathology Accreditation (CPA) company until recently, and is now part of the UKAS scheme.</p><p> </p><p>There is no intention to transfer the Lyme disease testing service from the Rare &amp; Imported Pathogens Laboratory (RIPL) to another laboratory. RIPL as a department will move from the Porton site as part of the PHE relocation scheduled to commence in 2018 but no decision on the exact date has been made. RIPL is scheduled to transfer to ISO 15189 in late summer 2016, when the ISO inspection team review the tests offered by the laboratory under ISO 15189. Until that time, the laboratory is operating under CPA in accordance with the transition process laid down by ISO.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL6109 ; HL6110","2016-02-24T13:10:53.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452164/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452164/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452164/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-10","Lyme Disease","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they intend to relocate testing for Lyme borreliosis away from the Rare and Imported Pathogens Laboratory; and if so, when they expect the move to take place, and whether the new laboratory will be ISO 15189 accredited at the time of the transfer.","false","Biography information for The Countess of Mar",,"The Countess of Mar","HL6111"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452165","Department of Health","false","2016-02-24","<p>The Department will review the terms of its grant awards and associated grant monitoring processes in line with guidance issued by the Cabinet Office on the 6 February 2016.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-02-24T13:07:47.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452165/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452165/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452165/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-10","Department of Health: Lobbying","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps the Department of Health plans to take to ensure that it complies with the announcement of the Cabinet Office on 6 February that no payments or grants awarded to organisations should be used for the influencing or attempted influencing of (1) Parliament, government or political parties, (2) the awarding or renewal of contracts and grants, or (3) legislative or regulatory action.","false","Biography information for Lord Naseby",,"Lord Naseby","HL6112"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452166","Department of Health","false","2016-02-24","<p>The conditions applicable to grants awarded to Action on Smoking and Health (ASH) are set out in the grant award letters, including a specific clause in the grant award letter which makes explicit that the award has been made under the provisions of Section 64 and may not be used for lobbying.</p><p> </p><p>ASH’s compliance with the conditions of the grant is assessed at the grant monitoring meetings held between the Deputy Director of tobacco control and representatives from ASH as well as in the final full year grant monitoring and governance reports.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-02-24T13:09:47.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452166/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452166/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452166/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-10","Action on Smoking and Health","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to review the grant awarded to the organisation Action on Smoking and Health in the current financial year in the light of the announcement by the Cabinet Office on 6 February in relation to charity funding.","false","Biography information for Lord Naseby",,"Lord Naseby","HL6113"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452167","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-24","<p>Sir Peter North’s 2010 Review of drink and drug driving made an assessment of various studies. The Coalition Government responded in March 2011 by setting out its position on maintaining the current limit. This Government agrees with that assessment and we do not believe any further studies have provided sufficient evidence to change that position. There are therefore no plans to change the current laws.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","HL6116","2016-02-24T12:20:04.08Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452167/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452167/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452167/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-10","Driving under Influence","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the risk of a driver's involvement in a collision involving injuries or death when they have a blood alcohol concentration of 80 milligrams of alcohol per 100 millilitres of blood or more; and how that assessment of risk compares with that made when the alcohol limit for drivers was set in 1967.","false","Biography information for Lord Rea",,"Lord Rea","HL6114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452168","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-24","<p>The Government advise drivers of the risks involved in driving after drinking alcohol in a number of ways.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for Transport’s THINK! drink drive campaign raises awareness of the risks and consequences of drink driving. The campaign aims to reinforce the social unacceptability of drink driving and achieve positive behaviour change amongst drivers.</p><p> </p><p>In December 2015, THINK! ran a £2.9 million drink drive campaign. This campaign targeted males aged 17-34, who are disproportionately represented in drink drive killed and seriously injured (KSI) casualty statistics. We advertised this campaign on TV, online video and radio, and supported this with wider PR and social media activity.</p><p> </p><p>In addition we work with partners including Coca-Cola, Budweiser and Johnnie Walker to provide incentives to drivers (such as buy one get one free soft drinks) to avoid drink driving.</p><p> </p><p>THINK! also provide materials to road safety professionals to run campaigns and provide information on the risks of drink driving to drivers locally.</p><p> </p><p>The driving theory test addresses the subject of drink driving and the topic is covered extensively in driving learning materials.</p><p> </p><p>The Government also works with organisations to provide Drink Drive Rehabilitation Schemes (DDRS) for first time offenders. The courses aim to allow reflection of behaviour and achieve behaviour change.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-02-24T12:21:14.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452168/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452168/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452168/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-10","Driving under Influence","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to advise drivers of the risks involved in driving after drinking alcohol.","false","Biography information for Lord Rea",,"Lord Rea","HL6115"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452169","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-24","<p>Sir Peter North’s 2010 Review of drink and drug driving made an assessment of various studies. The Coalition Government responded in March 2011 by setting out its position on maintaining the current limit. This Government agrees with that assessment and we do not believe any further studies have provided sufficient evidence to change that position. There are therefore no plans to change the current laws.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","HL6114","2016-02-24T12:20:04.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452169/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452169/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452169/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-10","Driving under Influence","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of recent studies of driver impairment after drinking alcohol, and whether those studies support the current alcohol limit for drivers.","false","Biography information for Lord Rea",,"Lord Rea","HL6116"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452170","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-25","<p>I refer the hon. Member to my recent answer (HL5950) to him on the same issue, to which I have nothing further to add.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-02-25T12:16:15.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452170/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452170/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452170/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Foreign Companies: Property","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when the consultation promised by the Prime Minister in his speech of 28 July 2015 at the Lee Kuan Yew School of Public Policy in Singapore regarding property ownership and "extending what we currently ask of UK companies to foreign companies" will commence.","false","Biography information for Lord Rooker",,"Lord Rooker","HL6117"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452171","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>In his Singapore speech the Prime Minister said the summit would take place in May 2016, a specific date will be announced in due course. The summit will bring together a range of governments and major international organisations in a commitment to strengthen the global response to corruption. On the involvement of the Overseas Territories, I refer the hon. Member to the Prime Minister’s response to the hon. Member for Hornsey and Wood Green (C21654) on 15th January 2016.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-02-25T15:14:59.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452171/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452171/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452171/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-10","Corruption","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government on what date the Anti-Corruption Summit in London referred to by the Prime Minister in his speech in Singapore on 28 July 2015 will take place; who will be invited; whether there will be opportunities for anti-corruption organisations to participate; and how the British Overseas Territories will be involved in that Summit.","false","Biography information for Lord Rooker",,"Lord Rooker","HL6118"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452172","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>Preparations for the Anti-Corruption Summit are being taken forward by the Joint Anti-Corruption Unit in the Cabinet Office, in close cooperation with a range of other government departments.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-02-25T15:21:05.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452172/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452172/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452172/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-10","Corruption","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government which department is leading on preparations for the Anti-Corruption Summit planned in London following the Prime Minister's Speech in Singapore on 28 July 2015.","false","Biography information for Lord Rooker",,"Lord Rooker","HL6119"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452173","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>Invitations will be sent out in due course.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-02-25T15:18:43.317Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452173/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452173/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452173/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-10","Corruption","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether UK political parties will be invited to attend and participate in the Anti-Corruption Summit planned in London following the Prime Minister's speech in Singapore on 28 July 2015.","false","Biography information for Lord Rooker",,"Lord Rooker","HL6120"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452174","Home Office","false","2016-02-23","<p>We continue to press the European Commission to revise the European Arrest Warrant handbook as soon as possible, in particular as it relates to proportionality. We have done so through both working groups in Brussels and bilateral contact.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2016-02-23T17:01:02.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452174/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452174/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452174/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-10","European Arrest Warrants","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had with the European Commission on when their revision of the European Arrest Warrant handbook will be issued.","false","Biography information for Lord Rowlands",,"Lord Rowlands","HL6121"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452175","Home Office","false","2016-02-23","<p>Figures for 2015 calendar year are not yet available. They will be released by the National Crime Agency when they have been verified later in the year. Figures for previous years are publically available at the National Crime Agency’s website at: http://www.nationalcrimeagency.gov.uk/publications/european-arrest-warrant-statistics</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2016-02-23T17:02:31.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452175/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452175/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452175/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-10","European Arrest Warrants","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what information they have on how many European Arrest Warrants were sought by individual member states in 2015, and how many were executed.","false","Biography information for Lord Rowlands",,"Lord Rowlands","HL6122"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452176","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-03","<p>The introduction of online voter registration makes it easier and faster to register to vote. This provided a platform for Bite the Ballot’s National Voter Registration Drive 2016 which made heavy use of on digital media. The Government supported the initiative by encouraging government departments and relevant stakeholders such as local authorities to promote it. Since its introduction, three quarters of applications to register to vote were made online by people aged 16-24. As part of the week long activity, my Rt Hon. Friend the Minister for Constitutional Reform met with representatives of several faith organisations to discuss democratic participation.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-03-03T17:20:14.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452176/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452176/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452176/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-10","Electoral Register: Young People","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action they have taken to support Bite the Ballot’s National Voter Registration Drive 2016, as well as the efforts by other organisations to engage and register (1) attainers, and (2) young voters, ahead of the elections in May and the EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Lord Wallace of Tankerness",,"Lord Wallace of Tankerness","HL6123"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452177","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>The announcement on 6 February was on a new clause for all government grant agreements. This new clause makes clear that grant recipients must not use the grant funding for political campaigning and lobbying unless it is expressly authorised in the grant agreement.</p><p> </p><p>Charities remain free to lobby the government, subject to charity law restrictions. They simply cannot use government grant funding to do so.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-02-25T15:14:28.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452177/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452177/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452177/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-10","Charities: Lobbying","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government to what extent their proposed new restrictions on lobbying by charities extend the existing restrictions imposed by charity legislation.","false","Biography information for Lord Beecham",,"Lord Beecham","HL6124"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452178","Department of Health","false","2016-02-24","<p>The NHS Trust Development Authority intends to publish the review as soon as possible. It is making publication arrangements in the light of its legal advice.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-02-24T13:07:18.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452178/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452178/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452178/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-10","Royal Wolverhampton NHS Trust","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why the NHS Trust Development Authority has not published the findings of the review of whistle-blowing and governance at the Royal Wolverhampton NHS Trust.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL6125"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452179","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-15","<p>As noble Lords would expect, the Government has carefully considered a range of legal issues in relation to the Trade Union Bill. The Government does not disclose the content or the source of its legal advice. It is essential to good government that ministers of the day are able to seek and receive legal advice on a confidential basis. To do otherwise might inhibit governments from seeking legal advice in the future.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-02-15T12:09:27.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452179/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452179/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452179/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-10","Trade Union Bill","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will publish the legal advice sought from First Treasury Counsel in relation to the impact of the Trade Union Bill on the devolved administrations of the UK, in particular in relation to Wales; and whether they will place a copy of that advice in the Library of the House.","false","Biography information for Baroness Morgan of Ely",,"Baroness Morgan of Ely","HL6126"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452180","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-22","<p>We are in regular contact with the British Olympic Association and British Paralympic Association and our advice to them is in line with the Government's travel advice. The Foreign and Commonwealth Office has updated its travel advice to affected countries, referring people to the National Travel Health Network and Centre (NaTHNaC) or to their medical professionals, if they have concerns. NaTHNaC has published specific advice for women who are pregnant to seek advice from a health professional before travel, and to consider avoiding travel to areas where Zika outbreaks are ongoing. Government continues to monitor the situation closely.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-02-22T14:59:15.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452180/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452180/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452180/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-10","Olympic Games: Brazil","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what advice they have offered the British Olympic Association regarding the potential health threat posed by the Zika virus to members of Team GB preparing in Brazil and competing at the Olympic and Paralympic Games in Rio de Janeiro.","false","Biography information for Lord Moynihan",,"Lord Moynihan","HL6127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452181","Home Office","false","2016-02-19","<p>We are unable to provide analysis for the arrests included in this report as the information is not centrally recorded in this way, and many of these investigations will be ongoing. However, the UK National Risk Assessment of Money Laundering and Terrorist Financing, released in October 2015, provides our assessment of the methods used to raise funds for terrorism in the UK, drawing on operational experience.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2016-02-19T12:45:13.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452181/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452181/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452181/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-10","Terrorism: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will provide an analysis of the main funding sources for those arrested in the UK for alleged terrorist activities as categorised in the 2015 <i>European Union Terrorism Situation and Trend Report</i>.","false","Biography information for Lord Stevenson of Balmacara",,"Lord Stevenson of Balmacara","HL6128"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452182","Attorney General","false","2016-02-23","<p>The Crown Prosecution Service is at present giving investigative advice to the Metropolitan Police Service (MPS) in respect of two pre charge investigations, which fall under Operation Tuleta and Operation Elveden.</p><p>In addition, the CPS has also received <a href="http://www.google.co.uk/url?sa=t&amp;rct=j&amp;q=&amp;esrc=s&amp;source=web&amp;cd=1&amp;cad=rja&amp;uact=8&amp;ved=0ahUKEwjjlrLjhovLAhVBRBoKHRvgAHUQFggcMAA&amp;url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.cps.gov.uk%2Fvictims_witnesses%2Fvictims_right_to_review%2F&amp;usg=AFQjCNHeGyqhHaYTDrDkhZu3pFimrhns8A&amp;bvm=bv.114733917,d.d2s" target="_blank">Victims' Right to Review </a>correspondence in relation to its recent decision not to charge ten individual journalists who worked at Mirror Group Newspapers for allegations of phone hacking at Mirror Group Newspapers, as part of Operation Golding. This correspondence is currently being considered.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2016-02-23T16:00:01.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452182/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452182/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452182/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-02-10","Culture, Practices and Ethics of the Press Inquiry","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Baroness Neville-Rolfe on 26 January (HL Deb, col 1152), which two cases remain outstanding in respect of preventing Leveson part 2 from taking place.","false","Biography information for Lord Stevenson of Balmacara",,"Lord Stevenson of Balmacara","HL6129"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452183","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>At the February European Council the Government negotiated a new settlement, giving the UK a special status in a reformed EU. The agreement sets out that the Treaties will be changed to “make it clear that the references to ever closer union do not apply to the United Kingdom” and acknowledges “different paths of integration being available for different Member States and do not compel all Member States to aim for a common destination.”</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-02-25T16:23:32.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452183/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452183/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452183/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-10","EU Integration","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the meeting on 9 February between the original member states of the EU, and the re-commitment by those member states to "an ever closer union" and a "two-speed Europe".","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL6130"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452184","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-02-24","<p>Commission proposals for a revision to the existing security of gas supply regulation were published on the 16 February. We will need to consider carefully the precise emergency arrangements that are proposed and how they might impact on the UK. These proposals will of course be subject to the usual negotiation process during which the Government will seek to achieve the best possible outcome for the UK. A final text will need to be agreed by qualified majority voting in the Council and in agreement with the European Parliament.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-02-24T12:39:25.007Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452184/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452184/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452184/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-10","Natural Gas: EU Action","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they anticipate imminent proposals by the European Commission compelling member states to send gas supplies to any other state in the case of emergencies; and if they expect such proposals to be brought forward, whether any decision would be taken by qualified majority voting or unanimity.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL6131"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452185","Department of Health","false","2016-02-24","<p>Our Childhood Obesity Strategy, which will be launched shortly, will look at everything that contributes to a child becoming overweight and obese including sugar.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-02-24T13:06:59.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452185/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452185/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452185/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-10","Sugar: Taxation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answers by Lord Prior of Brampton on 9 February (HL5598 and HL5599), whether they intend to reject calls to impose a sugar tax.","false","Biography information for Lord Stoddart of Swindon",,"Lord Stoddart of Swindon","HL6132"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452186","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-02-18","<p>There has been no ministerial direction given to the Permanent Secretary on spending plans for the Successor submarine programme.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-02-18T14:53:03.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452186/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452186/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/452186/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-02-10","Trident Submarines","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Earl Howe on 10 February (HL Deb, col 2239), whether a ministerial direction has been given to the Permanent Secretary in the Ministry of Defence to continue spending on the Vanguard successor submarine programme.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL6133"
