"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451670","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-02-22","<p>We are helping households to improve the energy efficiency of properties of all sizes through policies such as the Energy Company Obligation (ECO), which has already improved over 1.35 million properties. A reformed supplier obligation from April 2017 will upgrade the energy efficiency of well over 200,000 homes per year.</p><p> </p><p>Our Private Rented Sector Energy Efficiency Regulations made law from March 2015, will help up to 1 million domestic tenants in the private rented sector. This is expected to grow over time as people move from property to property.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-02-22T13:12:49.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451670/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451670/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451670/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-09","Housing: Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, what recent steps she has taken to improve the energy efficiency of small to mid-size properties.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","26421"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451671","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-02-22","<p>My Rt hon Friend the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions wrote to the Northern Ireland Executive in July 2015 on introduction of the life chances clauses in the Welfare Reform and Work Bill. As well as setting out the Government’s approach to child poverty and improving life chances, and inviting the Northern Ireland Executive to consider amendments they might wish to have introduced, he set out that he did not consider that legislative consent was required for any of the provisions as introduced.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2016-02-22T12:46:33.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451671/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451671/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451671/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-02-09","Welfare Reform and Work Bill","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, whether the amendments to the Child Poverty Act 2010 in the Welfare Reform and Work Bill require a Legislative Consent Motion to be brought before the Northern Ireland Assembly.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","26590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451672","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-02-22","<p>The Welfare Reform (Northern Ireland) Order 2015 does not include any reference to the Child Poverty Act 2010.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2016-02-22T12:48:15.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451672/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451672/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451672/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-02-09","Welfare Reform and Work Bill","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, whether the amendments to the Child Poverty Act 2010 in the Welfare Reform and Work Bill are included in the welfare clauses referred to in the Northern Ireland (Welfare Reform) Order 2015.","false","Biography information for Mark Durkan","Foyle","Mark Durkan","26591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451673","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-02-22","<p>Section 133 of the Criminal Justice Act 1988 requires the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland or, in relation to most criminal offences in Northern Ireland, the Department of Justice, to pay compensation where a person’s conviction for a criminal offence has been reversed or he has been pardoned on the grounds that a new or newly discovered fact shows beyond reasonable doubt that there has been a miscarriage of justice. The amount of compensation awarded in these cases is assessed by an independent assessor.</p><p>Section 175 of the Anti-social Behaviour, Crime and Policing Act 2014 inserted subsection (1ZA) into section 133 of the Criminal Justice Act 1988, providing a statutory definition of “miscarriage of justice”. In accordance with this new provision, the Secretary of State will only pay compensation for a “miscarriage of justice” where the new or newly discovered fact (on the basis of which the conviction was reversed) shows beyond reasonable doubt that the person did not commit the offence of which they were convicted. In Northern Ireland this new definition applies in relation to applications for compensation in cases involving sensitive national security information, which applications are determined by the Secretary of State rather than the Northern Ireland Department of Justice.</p><p>I believe that this clear definition enshrined in statute makes decisions on eligibility more transparent and less likely to be the subject of legal challenge and ensures (in those cases in Northern Ireland to which it applies) that compensation will only be paid where it is clear the person did not commit the offence of which they were convicted.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers","26437","2016-02-22T12:53:25.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451673/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451673/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451673/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-02-09","Miscarriages of Justice: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, if she will make an assessment of the effect of the application of section 133 of the Criminal Justice Act 1988 on the payment of compensation relating to cases in Northern Ireland; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Vernon Coaker","Gedling","Vernon Coaker","26436"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451674","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-02-22","<p>Section 133 of the Criminal Justice Act 1988 requires the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland or, in relation to most criminal offences in Northern Ireland, the Department of Justice, to pay compensation where a person’s conviction for a criminal offence has been reversed or he has been pardoned on the grounds that a new or newly discovered fact shows beyond reasonable doubt that there has been a miscarriage of justice. The amount of compensation awarded in these cases is assessed by an independent assessor.</p><p>Section 175 of the Anti-social Behaviour, Crime and Policing Act 2014 inserted subsection (1ZA) into section 133 of the Criminal Justice Act 1988, providing a statutory definition of “miscarriage of justice”. In accordance with this new provision, the Secretary of State will only pay compensation for a “miscarriage of justice” where the new or newly discovered fact (on the basis of which the conviction was reversed) shows beyond reasonable doubt that the person did not commit the offence of which they were convicted. In Northern Ireland this new definition applies in relation to applications for compensation in cases involving sensitive national security information, which applications are determined by the Secretary of State rather than the Northern Ireland Department of Justice.</p><p>I believe that this clear definition enshrined in statute makes decisions on eligibility more transparent and less likely to be the subject of legal challenge and ensures (in those cases in Northern Ireland to which it applies) that compensation will only be paid where it is clear the person did not commit the offence of which they were convicted.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers","26436","2016-02-22T12:53:25.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451674/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/