"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451703","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-17","<p>HM Revenue and Customs cannot comment on the affairs of individual employers. The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills set out how the Government operates civil and criminal enforcement of National Minimum Wage, which can be accessed by the link below:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/enforcing-national-minimum-wage-law" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/enforcing-national-minimum-wage-law</a></p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-17T10:00:19.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451703/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451703/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451703/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-09","Minimum Wage: Enforcement","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the press release of the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills of 5 February 2016, entitled New National Minimum Wage offenders named and shamed, for what reasons HM Revenue and Customs did not seek to prosecute Total Security Services Limited for non-payment of minimum wage arrears.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","26430"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451704","Home Office","false","2016-02-12","<p>The cases referred to in the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman report do not reflect current visa and asylum processes. We have made significant improvements in our handling of complaints in recent years and have a clear plan to improve this element of our service further.</p><p>This plan takes account of feedback from the Public and Health Services Ombudsman and we will continue to work with the Ombudsman to identify further service improvements.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-02-12T11:04:49.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451704/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451704/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451704/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-09","Home Office: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department plans to take to implement the recommendations of the Parliamentary and Health Service Ombudsman in its Insights into selected government departments, published on 10 November 2015, on scrutiny of the quality of its overall performance.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","26621"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451705","Department for Education","false","2016-02-22","<p>The department has issued best practice guidance for all schools on the need to give high priority to the consideration of cost for parents. The guidance sets out that governing bodies should be able to demonstrate that they have obtained the best value for money from suppliers, and that any savings negotiated with suppliers should be passed on to parents wherever possible. It also makes clear that schools should not enter into cash back arrangements.</p><p>We have recently announced that we intend to put school uniform guidance on a statutory footing. The school uniform guidance is available at: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/school-uniform" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/school-uniform</a></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2016-02-22T17:48:52.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451705/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451705/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451705/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-02-09","Schools: Uniforms","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on schools asking uniform suppliers for discounts or commission on school uniform sales; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dame Cheryl Gillan","Chesham and Amersham","Mrs Cheryl Gillan","26585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451706","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-15","<p>We have given careful thought to the practical implications of the transition period and the possible safeguards that can be built in to the Bill to help maintain bus service levels for passengers. The Bill is still being drafted and it is therefore too early to confirm the detail of the process that may be proposed through the Bill.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-02-15T14:19:59.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451706/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451706/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451706/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-09","Bus Services: Franchises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he plans to take to ensure that bus service levels are maintained during the transition period before the introduction of a bus franchise.","false","Biography information for Sir Graham Brady","Altrincham and Sale West","Mr Graham Brady","26488"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451707","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-15","<p>The Buses Bill will introduce new powers for local authorities to franchise their local bus services. The Bill is still being drafted and it is therefore too early to confirm the detail of the process that may be proposed through the Bill.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-02-15T14:28:26.82Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451707/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451707/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451707/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-09","Bus Services: Franchises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what criteria he plans that local authorities will be expected to meet in order to justify bus franchising in their areas; and whether he plans that assessment will be subject to independent assessment.","false","Biography information for Sir Graham Brady","Altrincham and Sale West","Mr Graham Brady","26489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451708","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-15","<p>The actual costs and benefits will depend on how franchising is implemented at the local level. The potential impacts of the Buses Bill proposals will be set out in the Impact Assessment which will accompany the introduction of the Bill.</p><p> </p><p>When considering the costs of bus franchising it will be important for the authority to consider alternatives as well as the costs and benefits of proposals.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-02-15T14:32:14.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451708/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451708/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451708/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-09","Bus Services: Franchises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what assessment his Department has made of the costs of bus franchising outside London.","false","Biography information for Sir Graham Brady","Altrincham and Sale West","Mr Graham Brady","26490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451709","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-15","<p>My Department has not yet entered into discussions with the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills on the effect of bus franchising on the vehicle manufacturing sector. My officials have, however, discussed proposals with the Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-02-15T14:52:59.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451709/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451709/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451709/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-09","Bus Services: Franchises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions his Department has had with the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills on the effect of bus franchising on the vehicle manufacturing sector.","false","Biography information for Sir Graham Brady","Altrincham and Sale West","Mr Graham Brady","26533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451710","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-15","<p>Local transport authority with access to bus franchising powers will wish to ensure that local operators are aware of their intentions, so that investment decisions can be taken and services continue to be provided in the best interests of passengers</p><p> </p><p>Any authority that chooses to implement franchising will have the ability to specify its requirements of operators as part of any franchise contract. This could include requirements relating to the standards of vehicles to be used by operators.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-02-15T14:56:56.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451710/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451710/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451710/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-09","Bus Services: Franchises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that bus operators are incentivised to invest in new vehicles when franchising is an option open to local authorities after plans for the devolution of that policy are implemented.","false","Biography information for Sir Graham Brady","Altrincham and Sale West","Mr Graham Brady","26623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451711","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-17","<p>The Housing Investment Fund is a loan, supported by a legal agreement in place between Manchester City Council (as the lead authority for the Greater Manchester Combined Authority) and DCLG. All of the Housing Investment Fund must be used as financial transactions to private sector organisations for the funding to qualify under the terms of that legal agreement.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-02-17T14:27:49.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451711/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451711/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451711/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-09","Housing: Greater Manchester","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what proportion of the Housing Investment Fund devolved to Greater Manchester Combined Authority homes over 10 years is in the form of (a) loans and (b) grants.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","26659"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451712","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-17","<p>The Housing Market Renewal Pathfinders programme ran from 2002 to 2011 and created large-scale Whitehall targets for demolition and clearance across the Midlands and the North of England. The programme was cancelled under the last Government.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-02-17T14:30:17.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451712/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451712/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451712/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-09","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what assessment he has made of the effect of the withdrawal of the Housing Market Renewal Initiative.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","26660"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451713","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-15","<p><strong>Proposals are developed by and belong to local areas, therefore publication of proposals is a matter for individual places. Agreed devolution deal documents are published on the gov.uk website. </strong></p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-02-15T10:59:57.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451713/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451713/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451713/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-09","Stamp Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with which local authorities and combined authorities his Department is in discussions on retention of Stamp Duty income by local bodies.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","26662"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451714","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-11","<p>HM Revenue and Customs is responsible for the conduct of tax enquiries, and Ministers are not informed of the progress of enquiries and play no part in agreeing the amount of tax to be paid by any taxpayer.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-11T08:57:35.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451714/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451714/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451714/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-09","Google: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he was made aware of HM Revenue and Customs' original estimate of tax due by Google prior to the recent tax settlement with that company.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","26663"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451715","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-16","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave to him on 5 February 2016 to UIN: 25342.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-02-16T15:25:49.523Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451715/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451715/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451715/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-09","Public Sector: Oldham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what land and property in Oldham his Department has identified for disposal as part of the One Public Estate programme over the next five years.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","26658"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451716","Home Office","false","2016-02-12","<p>As part of the regional dispersal policy for asylum seekers established in 2000, the advisory cluster limit of 1 asylum seeker for every 200 of the settled population, applies to local authority area level only. Data on the numbers of asylum seekers in local authority areas is published and can be found at (Asylum Vol 4. Table 16q). https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-july-to-september-2015/asylum.</p><p>Data is not collated at ward or constituency level and to do so would incur disproportionate costs, it may also be precluded by the provisions of the Data Protection Act, given that individuals could reasonably be identified through the release of such data.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-02-12T11:06:15.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451716/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451716/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451716/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-09","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, which electoral wards in England have exceeded a one in 200 saturation level for asylum placements; and by what percentage each such ward has exceeded that level.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","26661"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451717","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-17","<p>Since the UK’s first Cyber Security Strategy was published in 2011, we have invested £860m in a National Cyber Security Programme to support the UK’s economic prosperity, protect our national security and safeguard the public’s way of life by building a more trusted and resilient digital environment. The National Cyber Security Programme’s budget breaks down annually as follows: 2011/12 – £105m 2012/13 – £155m 2013/14 – £180m 2014/15 – £210m 2015/16 – £210m We are investing £1.9bn in the next Cyber Security Programme, from financial years 2016/17 until 2020/21, which will give the UK the next generation of cyber security and make our country one of the safest places to do business online.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-02-17T16:13:56.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451717/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451717/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451717/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-09","Cybercrime: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much has been spent by the National Cyber Security Programme in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Steven Paterson","Stirling","Steven Paterson","26550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451718","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-15","<p>The Office of Cyber Security and Information Assurance (OCSIA) in the National Security Secretariat in the Cabinet Office works with a range of government partners to deliver the National Cyber Security Programme (NCSP). OCSIA has been working closely with the Department for Communities and Local Government (DCLG) to support local government cyber security. This includes working with individual councils, the Society of IT Management (SOCITM), the Society of Local Authority Chief Executive (SOLACE) and the Local Government Association (LGA). This financial year the NSCP funded team within DCLG has delivered regional workshops for local government leaders with further workshops planned later this year.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-02-15T13:30:23.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451718/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451718/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451718/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-09","Local Government: Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what recent discussions his Department has held with local authorities on cyber-security.","false","Biography information for Steven Paterson","Stirling","Steven Paterson","26551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451719","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-02-17","<p>The Government’s National Cyber Security Programme (NCSP) aims to tackle cyber crime and make the UK the safest place in the world to do business in the world. This includes the Cyber Essentials Scheme to protect businesses against common cyber threats and the cyber streetwise campaign which offers simple cyber security advice to small businesses and consumers. In addition to the £860 million investment under the NCSP between 2011-2016, in November 2015 the Chancellor announced a new five year £1.9 billion investment in cyber security to make the UK one of the best protected countries in cyber space.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2016-02-17T16:12:36.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451719/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451719/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451719/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-02-09","Cybercrime: Small Businesses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what steps his Department is taking to help small and medium-sized enterprises protect themselves against cyber-attack.","false","Biography information for Steven Paterson","Stirling","Steven Paterson","26549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451720","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Government has announced that, by the end of the Parliament, we will give all local councils, including city regions, new responsibilities in return for keeping 100% of locally raised business rates. We will also give city regions powers over setting local business rates, strengthening their link with their local business communities and allowing them to tailor local taxes to the needs of their local economies. We will be working out the details of the reform in the coming months in consultation with local government.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-02-29T17:02:38.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451720/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451720/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451720/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-09","Non-domestic Rates: Devolution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what projections his Department has made of the effect on business rates receipts of plans for devolved city region authorities.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","26493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451721","Home Office","false","2016-02-12","<p>Any migrant death is a tragedy and the international community must act to reduce the likelihood of more migrants losing their lives in this way or falling victim to smuggling and trafficking.</p><p>The Government believes it is better to prioritise interventions upstream in countries of origin and transit in ways that reduce the need of migrants to leave their country of origin or move on from a safe third country. The UK is at the forefront of the response to the crisis in Syria and the region. On 4 February 2016, the Prime Minister announced that the UK will more than double our total pledge to the Syria crisis from £1.12 billion to over £2.3 billion. This is our largest ever response to a single humanitarian crisis.</p><p>Furthermore, more than $11 billion was pledged at the Supporting Syria Conference the UK co-hosted in London on 4th February, the largest amount raised in one day for a humanitarian crisis. The international community has pledged nearly $6 billion for 2016; with a further $5 billion for the coming years until 2020.</p><p>However, for those individuals who cannot be supported in the region, the UK operates three resettlement programmes: Gateway, Mandate and the Syrian Resettlement Scheme. These provide a safe and direct route to the UK for the most vulnerable UNHCR recognised refugees.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-02-12T11:04:12.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451721/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451721/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451721/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-09","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the potential effect of establishment of safe and legal routes for asylum seekers wishing to enter the UK on the frequency of migrant deaths at sea.","false","Biography information for Ms Diane Abbott","Hackney North and Stoke Newington","Ms Diane Abbott","26637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451722","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-15","<p>DFID is providing nearly £46 million to support refugees in Europe. Part of this funding will provide shelter, warm clothes, food, and medical supplies, including for 27,000 children and babies, many of whom have fled fighting in Syria.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2016-02-15T11:33:00.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451722/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451722/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451722/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-09","Syria: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what support her Department is providing for (a) Syrian refugees and (b) Syrian refugee children in Europe; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ms Diane Abbott","Hackney North and Stoke Newington","Ms Diane Abbott","26638"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451723","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-15","<p>DFID is funding work on mental health in several of our focus countries. For example in Malawi, under the Health Partnership Scheme DFID is helping to establish a community-based programme to improve care of people with common and severe mental health illnesses.</p><p>The UK is also providing mental health services through the provision of mobile clinics, healthcare and emergency surgery for Syrian refugees caught up in the ongoing crisis</p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2016-02-15T11:32:01.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451723/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451723/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451723/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-09","Developing Countries: Mental Illness","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what steps her Department is taking to reduce the high incidence of mental health disorders in countries (a) with poor mental health support services and (b) that are experiencing conflict or have recently emerged from conflict; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ms Diane Abbott","Hackney North and Stoke Newington","Ms Diane Abbott","26636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451724","Home Office","false","2016-02-18","<p>Border Force is undertaking a vital role in the search and rescue of migrants crossing the Mediterranean, as part of a Frontex led programme. Border Force carried out for the Department for International Development (DFID) funded search and rescue missions in Summer 2015 and is currently undertaking a second DFID funded deployment, which is due to end on 30th April 2016. Given the significant contribution made to date, it is likely that Frontex will invite Border Force to continue its involvement in future search and rescue programmes and Border Force is therefore currently establishing its Mediterranean role after 30th April 2016 and the availability of further DFID funding.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-02-18T16:43:58.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451724/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451724/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451724/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-09","Rescue Services: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when her Department's funding to sea search and rescue programmes are due to end; what future funding is planned for such programmes; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Ms Diane Abbott","Hackney North and Stoke Newington","Ms Diane Abbott","26639"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451725","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-29","<p>Treasury Ministers and officials have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery.</p><p> </p><p>Details of ministerial and permanent secretary meetings with external organisations on departmental business are published on a quarterly basis and are available at:</p><p><a href="http://www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/minister_hospitality.htm" target="_blank">http://www.hm-treasury.gov.uk/minister_hospitality.htm</a></p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-29T16:00:17.487Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451725/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451725/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451725/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-09","Revenue and Customs: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent discussions he has had with HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) on that body's record of (a) call waiting times, (b) call handling and (c) the steps HMRC plans to take to increase the level of service to telephone customers.","false","Biography information for Bridget Phillipson","Houghton and Sunderland South","Bridget Phillipson","26620"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451726","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-16","<p>At the “Supporting Syria and the Region London 2016” Conference we co-hosted on 4<sup>th</sup> February 2016, leaders came together to pledge more than $11 billion, the largest amount raised in one day for a humanitarian crisis. Commitments made at the Conference will help to create 1.1 million jobs and provide education to an additional 1 million children. The protection of civilians was at the heart of the Conference. Participants agreed to use their influence with all parties to the conflict to halt abuses, to allow humanitarian agencies rapid, safe and unimpeded access throughout Syria in order to reach besieged and hard-to-reach areas. The outcomes of the conference are reflected in the Co-hosts' statement available on the Conference website <a href="http://www.supportingsyria2016.com/" target="_blank">www.supportingsyria2016.com</a>.</p><p>The UK condemns the actions of the Syrian regime, driving civilians from their homes in and around Aleppo, and the role of Russia in supporting this offensive. We are deeply concerned by reports that over 30,000 civilians have been newly displaced from Aleppo City and other areas of northern Syria between 1<sup>st</sup> and 8<sup>th</sup> February. This is on top of the existing 36,000 internally displaced persons from Aleppo City.</p><p>DFID continues to use existing funding to support our partners to be flexible in their responses and to enable the realignment of programming to meet those newly displaced and most in need. We also support the UN OCHA managed, Humanitarian Pooled Fund (HPF), which has announced a US$10.5 million emergency fund to meet the needs of the new displaced as a result of the fighting in northern Aleppo. The HPF funding will focus on meeting key health, WASH, food, shelter and protection needs.</p>","New Forest West","Mr Desmond Swayne",,"2016-02-16T15:04:52.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451726/answer","Biography information for Sir Desmond Swayne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451726/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451726/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-09","Syria: Refugees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment she has made of the effect of the recent fighting around Aleppo on refugee numbers.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","26555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451727","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-07","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>In formulating its final proposals, the Government has carefully considered all the evidence submitted during the consultation process.</p><p> </p><p>A number of respondents expressed concern that extended opening hours could increase pressure on shop workers to work longer hours on Sundays. We therefore propose to enable shop workers to opt out of working additional hours on Sundays, to shorten the notice period for shop workers at large shops who wish to opt out of Sunday working altogether, and to strengthen and clarify the duty on employers to notify shop workers of their opt-out rights.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-07T17:20:34.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451727/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451727/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451727/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-09","Sunday Trading: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, if he will make an assessment of the implications for his Department's policies on shop workers' rights to opt out of Sunday working of the findings of a recent USDAW survey on the number of shop workers who (a) feel under pressure to work longer hours on a Sunday and (b) want to work fewer hours on a Sunday.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","26601"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451728","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-22","<p>Environmental law is an area of devolved competence. Transposition and implementation of EU environmental law therefore rests with the devolved administrations. The obligation to transpose and implement EU environmental law applies across the whole of the UK.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-02-22T12:28:06.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451728/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451728/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451728/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-09","Environment Protection: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, if she will provide an estimate of the number of environmental laws, derived from the EU, that are (a) ignored and (b) unused by the devolved administrations.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","26438"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451729","Department of Health","false","2016-02-12","<p>Information on why a drug has been prescribed is not collected.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-02-12T16:25:21.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451729/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451729/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/451729/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-09","Urinary Tract Infections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the cost to the NHS of antibiotics used to treat urinary tract infections in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Gavin Robinson","Belfast East","Gavin Robinson","26426"
